    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1985-02-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1985-02-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="240"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d240">
                <head>240. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_LRB_1">Richard Levine</persName> of
                    the National Security Council Staff to the President’s Deputy Assistant for
                    National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_PJM_1"
                        >Poindexter</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d240fn1">Source:
                        Reagan Library, African Affairs Directorate, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                            >NSC</gloss>: Records, <gloss target="#t_AF_1">AF</gloss> Famine:
                        [02/05/85–11/05/85]. Confidential. Sent for information. Copies were sent to
                            <persName corresp="#p_MDW_1">McMinn</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_RPH_1">Ringdahl</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1985-02-15">February 15, 1985</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Food for Progress Update</item>
                </list>
                <p>At my request, Dan Amstutz, Under Secretary of Agriculture, chaired a meeting
                    today to finalize cost figures for the four “Food for Progress” funding options,
                    consistent with the Administration’s 1985 farm bill. State, <gloss
                        target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss>, Treasury and I participated. The final
                    funding costs are as follows:</p>
                <table cols="3">
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">Four-year Budget Cost</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>(1) </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">
                                <persName corresp="#p_KRB_1">Keating</persName> option:</hi> takes
                            food from existing <gloss target="#t_CCC_1">CCC</gloss> stocks<note
                                n="2" xml:id="d240fn2">
                                <gloss target="#t_CCC_1">CCC</gloss>
                                <hi rend="italic">must</hi> be reimbursed for food given away that
                                it otherwise <hi rend="italic">could</hi> sell. [Footnote is in the
                                original.]</note> under expanded 416 program; fund transportation
                            with new money.</cell>
                        <cell>$405M</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>(2) </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">
                                <gloss target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss> option:</hi> seek all new money
                            for food and transport.</cell>
                        <cell>$391M</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>(3) </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">
                                <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> option:</hi> take food from
                            Title I program, fund transport with new money.</cell>
                        <cell>$160M</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>(4) </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">
                                <gloss target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss> option:</hi> take food and
                            transport money from Title I program.</cell>
                        <cell>0</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>These numbers are authoritative and consistent with the Administration’s farm
                    bill. <persName corresp="#p_KRB_1">Bob Keating</persName>’s assertion of zero
                    budget costs for his <gloss target="#t_CCC_1">CCC</gloss> option<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d240fn3">See <ref target="#d236fn4">footnote 4, Document
                        236</ref>.</note> stems from a misunderstanding of how the Commodity Credit
                    Corporation functions financially and the central theme of our new farm bill
                    which is to remove the <gloss target="#t_USG_1">USG</gloss> from rebuilding
                    government food stocks.</p>
                <p>The month I have spent on this study I feel has been time well used because it
                    will allow us to choose far more efficient funding <pb facs="0690" n="644"
                        xml:id="pg_644"/> options. It has taken this long to come up with solid
                    numbers because these derive from the farm bill’s policy effects.</p>
                <p>I expect the full “Food for Progress” implementation papers will be ready late
                    next week, including sections on funding options, country selection criteria to
                    be applied (there is interagency consensus on this) and administrative
                        options.<note n="4" xml:id="d240fn4">See <ref target="#d244">Document
                            244</ref>.</note> Also, my work on the Bonn Summit papers<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d240fn5">Not further identified.</note> on food aid initiatives are
                    now part of the Sherpa team papers.</p>
            </div>
